and Projections (database), May. Budget control and financial management The new framework will only be effective if the government is able to implement its budget plans and 
prevent slippages (Figure 5). In the past, inadequate monitoring has undermined the government's ability 
to achieve its targets, as evidenced by the generation of various contingent liabilities and payment arrears, 
as well as the frequent need to pass supplementary budgets to cover expenditure overruns despite the 
existence of a central budget contingency fund. Spending control efforts are hampered by the highly 
fragmented nature of financial reporting even at the central government level. Over 500 individual central 
government spending units report to the Ministry of Finance. The detailed monitoring and control of so 
many spending units leaves very little resources for the Ministry of Finance to get an overall view of 
individual ministries and major spending areas and therefore exercise effective budget control (OECD, 
