good value for money and not to postpone expenditure. The literature and international experience suggest 
a number of factors that can help to ensure that a PPP is the right delivery model and maximises value for 
money. These include specifying contracts in terms of outputs instead of inputs in order to maximise the 
benefits of private sector technical expertise and management skills; an ex ante evaluation of PPP versus 
public procurement; a public body obtaining planning and environmental permissions in advance of tender 
to avoid delays; and proper fiscal accounting for PPPs including recording them in contingent liabilities 
(Araújo and Sutherland, 2010). By international standards, the efficiency enhancing features of Portugal's PPP framework appear 
relatively strong on paper and the government is intending further improvements (Figure 11). It is setting 
